title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant w/ammo and extras
postcontent:
Here's a more or less complete shooter's Mosin Nagant package.

The Rifle:

1939 Izhevsk 91/30.  It's a Molot refurb, no cosmoline.  The bore is in excellent shape (see pic below).  Not counterbored.  All numbers match--there is an Arsenal strikethrough/renumber on the floor plate but bolt/receiver/butt are all original.  The wood is beautiful, but shows a couple of relatively fresh minor scratches (poorly packed bayonet in the import shipment). Comes with bayonet (packed in bubblewrap in the pic--I've never taken it out), oil can, cleaning bits, and manual (a Molot manual translated into English ... with sometimes entertaining results).

The Ammo (not pictured):

*A full case (two 440 rd. spam cans) of Romanian surplus Ammo.  One can has been opened, and a couple of rounds have been fired (what? I was curious ... and yes, they went boom). Opener is included, as it the cool wooden box.
*40 rounds of loose surplus FMJ (bought in 20 rd packets)
*20 rounds of Wolf FMJ
*20 rounds of Prvi Partizan SPBT

The Extras:

*Otis ripcord in .30 (it works well, but it's barely long enough for this monster-you have to push it as far down as you can, and then screw a brush into the muzzle end to get enough of a grip to pull it through.  This barrel ain't short)
*3 new .30 bore swabs
*One extra wooden stock (no handguard or metal bits), and an extra recoil crossbolt to fit it.

It's a fun shooter. I've only had it to the range twice, however--it is a fairly recent purchase, and I was hoping for a long and beautiful friendship, but then my wife got pregnant with our third, and our car only has four seats.  The new math says new car, and thus the hobby takes a hit.  So it goes.

FTF only, 2 forms of ID and all that.  I'm willing to meet in Richmond, Norther Va, or in the Piedmont, generally.

title: For Sale:  VERY RARE REMINGTON 720A CAMP PERRY PRIZE RIFLE
location: South Carolina, South Carolina, United States
postcontent:
This rifle is in pristine condition and is in the original box, serial # dates it to 1943 production. proof marks on the stock confirm it to be a Camp Perry Prize Rifle. There will not be to many chances to own one of these very rare hitoical rifles. See the story from The National Firearms Museum below;

The Model 720A was produced between 1941 and 1944, with a total production of approximately 2500 rifles. Of these, nearly 1000, including the example seen here, were purchased in 1942 by the Navy Department and were awarded as trophies to winning Navy and Marine Corps personnel in a variety of competitions. These trophy guns can be identified by the Ordnance crossed cannon and inspector's proof marks on the stock.



The Remington Model 720 bolt action rifle, intended to compete with Winchester's popular Model 70, was produced in limited numbers until Second World War military requirements forced its discontinuation. Even some knowledgeable collectors and firearms historians may not be familiar with these rifles. Introduced by Remington in mid- to late-1941, the Model 720 was billed as an improvement over its predecessor, the Model 30S. The Ilion, New York arms maker offered these in .270 Winchester and .257 Roberts chamberings, as well as in .30-Ã06; and with barrel lengths of 20-, 22-, and 24 inches.



Other features included a semi-beavertail stock with checkered pistol grip and fore end; checkered steel butt plate; hinged floor plate; swept-back bolt handle, and speed-lock firing pin which cocked on the opening of the bolt. Remington intended to phase out the Model 30 shortly after this new design hit the market, but the Pearl Harbor attack and the subsequent U.S. entry into the



Second World War threw a wrench into Remington's plans. Production of the 720 was soon discontinued as military ordnance contracts for the Model 1903A1 and the later M1903A3 took over the company's production line. Following are serial numbers and production totals by year for the Model 720: Year Serial Numbers Production Total 1941 40000 - 40427 427 1942 40428 - 41449 1,022 1943 41450 - 42422 973 1944 42423 - 42427 5 _______ 2,427 Eventually, existing Model 720 inventories in .30-Ã06 caliber, as well as various incomplete sub-assemblies, were "drafted" into military service by the U.S. Navy. These rifles are easily distinguished by the "crossed cannon" Ordnance proof mark and inspector's cartouche on the stock. These rifles would never see combat service; instead, they spent the war in storage at the Navy's Crane, Indiana Ammunition Depot.



There they would remain, until an order for their destruction as surplus property was issued in 1963. Fortunately, Major Kam Hayden, U.S.M.C., who had just finished a tour as commander of the Marine Corps Marksmanship Training Unit at Quantico, Virginia, heard about the proposal to destroy these rifles. Maj. Hayden suggested that they be awarded as trophies to top Navy and Marine Corps competitive shooters.



This plan was approved, and beginning in 1964, the Model 720 was designated as the "Secretary of the Navy Trophy." A few rifles exhibited ill-effects from their long storage and were subsequently used as a source of parts, while the remaining inventory was divided between the Navy and Marine Corps to be awarded to winners at the National Matches at Camp Perry, Ohio, and at various divisional and inter-service matches. Presented in their original shipping cartons, these Secretary of the Navy trophy rifles feature an engraved magazine floorplate identifying the competition for which they were awarded. Some shooters won as many as seven of these rare trophies before steps were taken to limit the awarding of a rifle.

Hello there! This machine is a 220V Hobart Handler 187 MIG Welder. It operates on a dryer plug and can weld 1/4" Steel, or can weld 1/8" Aluminum. 

I bought this machine brand new in early 2011 (I *might* be able to dig up my original reciept) and only used it for a short while before I was offered a much larger machine for a deal that I couldn't refuse. This has been my backup machine ever since.

Anyway, it was $700 new + tax. I've added the following upgrades:

Flex Head MIG Gun (Highly durable and the nozzle moves in any direction. Great for exhaust welding, auto body work, etc). Cost $180

Flowmeter... Better quality and more precise gas measurement than the stock regulator. $50.

(Upgraded ground clamp, jar of nozzle gel, and a few extra nozzles... $30 retail for all)

The total new cost of this setup is $960, so I'd give it a lightly used trade value of about $700ish (+ or -). You'll still need a gas cylinder and a welding helmet tho (sorry, I dont have extras of those).

Not really looking to sell, just wanting to trade for something to add to my collection.
